[4] Taiwan
Date: Thu 28 Aug 2008
From: Wu Ping-Fuai <f10282@cdc.gov.tw>


In Taiwan, the primary control measure against dengue adopted is to
eliminate vector breeding sites. In order to prevent the occurrence of
dengue fever outbreaks, Taiwan CDC (Centers for Disease Control) often
appeals to communities and members of the public to mobilize cleanup
efforts to eliminate vector breeding sites.

On the other hand, insecticide spraying is a short term emergency measure
implemented in Taiwan to prevent further transmission of dengue viruses and
occurrence of dengue epidemics. The goal of this measure is for the local
government to immediately apply chemical control of mosquitoes to the place
where the case possibly became infected and the places that the case had
visited after disease onset. Effective spraying of insecticides will result
in killing of dengue virus-carrying _Aedes_ mosquitoes and cutting off the
circle of transmission.

--
Wu Ping-Fuai
Division Director
Second Division
Taiwan Centers for Disease Control
<f10282@cdc.gov.tw>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Wu Ping-Fuai for this information and would be
interested in receiving details about the Taiwan approach to
community-based efforts to eliminate or reduce _Aedes_ breeding sites. Dr
Wu Ping-Fuai is correct -- elimination of these breeding sites is the most
effective means for vector mosquito population reduction over the
long-term, but has been difficult to accomplish and sustain in most
countries. We wish them success. - Mod.TY]

